    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Beyond Python's built-in list, dict, and set, classical data structures — stacks, queues, heaps, graphs, and trees — model agent workflows: pending tool calls, priority scheduling, plan graphs, and hierarchical context. Choosing the right structure affects correctness, ordering, and performance of orchestration logic."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What it is"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "data structure",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " organizes data to support specific operations efficiently. Agent code uses both Python builtins and conceptual structures implemented with them or with "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "collections",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " / "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "heapq",
            "marks": [
